Diagnosis. Females can be easily recognised by the very small epigynal ridges (
Fig. 52
) and the nearly transverse copulatory ducts bent at a right angle medially (
Fig. 53
). The male is unique amongst the African species in having a prolateral and retrolateral spine in the proximal third of the cymbium dorsally (
Fig. 55
), as well as by the relatively short and strongly curved distal coil of the embolus (
Fig. 54
).

Distribution. Known only from two localities in Central and West Africa (
Fig. 68
).
